[{"id":"VR803414","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of two spheres at two different times. The spheres are labeled Sphere 1 and Sphere 2, where Sphere 1 has radius R and sphere 2 has radius 3 R. A wire connects the two spheres, and the wire contains an open switch. In the first view, sphere 1 has charge lowercase q sub 1 equals uppercase Q, and sphere 2 has charge lowercase q sub 2 equals 0, and the switch is then closed. In the second view, the switch is opened again. For sphere 1, the charge lowercase q sub 1 and electric potential V sub 1 are now unknown. For sphere 2, the charge lowercase q sub 2 and electric potential V sub 2 are now unknown.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR803414.g03.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Conducting Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> with radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> is charged with charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mstyle></math></span></span>. Conducting Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> with radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3 R\"><math alttext=\"3 R\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi></math></span></span> is initially uncharged. A switch briefly connects the two spheres, then is disconnected, as shown. Afterwards Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> has charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase q sub 1\"><math alttext=\"lowercase q sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>q</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> and the electric potential at its surface is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub 1\"><math alttext=\"V sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> while Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> has charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase q sub 2\"><math alttext=\"lowercase q sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>q</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> and the electric potential at its surface is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"V sub 2\"><math alttext=\"V sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>. Which of the following correctly compares the charges on the two spheres and the electric potential at the surface of each sphere after the wire has been removed?</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1\"/><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Charges</th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">Electric potentials</th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase q sub 1 equals lowercase q sub 2\"><math alttext